{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12497"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12497"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.89,0.06,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by ambulance. His girlfriend last saw him 24 hours ago, and this morning found him unresponsive on the floor of his bedroom with an empty 1L bottle of vodka, an empty packet of 24 diazepam tablets, and an empty box of 100 paracetamol tablets (500mg) next to him. On examination, he is drowsy, diaphoretic and has diffuse abdominal tenderness. His blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 120/min, respiratory rate 20/min and oxygen saturation 95% on room air. He denies any other medical history or drug use. His laboratory tests show an elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) level of 800 U/L (0-40) and a paracetamol level of 150 mcg/mL (\u0026lt;10).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activated charcoal and observe for 6 hours","N-acetylcysteine (NAC) immediately","Intravenous fluids and monitor liver function tests","Flumazenil","Fomepizole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation and history are consistent with a paracetamol overdose. The laboratory results show an elevated ALT level and paracetamol level. The initial management should include \u003Cstrong\u003Eadministering N-acetylcysteine (NAC) immediately \u003C/strong\u003Eespecially because of the unclear timeline since ingestion of the drug and most likely ingestion of more than 200mg/kg since an empty box of paracetamol tablets was found near him. NAC is an antidote that can prevent or decrease liver damage caused by paracetamol toxicity. NAC works by increasing the levels of glutathione in the liver, which can neutralise the toxic metabolites of paracetamol and protect the liver from damage. NAC is most effective when administered within 8-10 hours of paracetamol ingestion, but it can still be effective up to 36 hours after ingestion in some cases. The intravenous route of administration is preferred in patients with suspected or confirmed paracetamol overdose and the recommended dose and duration of NAC treatment depend on the severity of paracetamol toxicity and the patient\u0027s liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering activated charcoal and observing for 6 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective intervention if given within 1 hour of ingestion, as it can adsorb the drug and reduce absorption from the gut. However, in this case, the patient\u0027s presentation suggests that the overdose occurred more than 1 hour ago and the drug has already been absorbed. Therefore, activated charcoal is not appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous fluids and monitoring liver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as supportive treatment to maintain blood pressure and renal perfusion, but they do not have a direct effect on liver damage caused by paracetamol overdose. Monitoring liver function tests is important in evaluating the extent of liver damage and assessing the efficacy of NAC therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepine poisoning can result in sedation and less commonly, in respiratory depression. While an overdose of diazepam (e.g. rapid ingestion of 24 tablets) may explain this patient\u0027s drowsiness, it is less likely to cause abdominal pain than paracetamol overdose. \u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil \u003C/strong\u003Eis a benzodiazepine antagonist, that is most commonly used to reverse procedural sedation, and has a limited role in the management of benzodiazepine poisoning. Among other contraindications for, flumazenil is contraindicated in patients with a known seizure disorder, or a known or suspected benzodiazepine dependence, as it can precipitate seizures that may be difficult to control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFomepezil \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inhibitor of alcohol dehydrogenase, that has traditionally been used as an antidote for methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning, however there is emerging evidence for its efficacy as an adjunctive therapy for paracetamol toxicity. However, there are no established guidelines or randomised control trials on this subject, and regardless, NAC is a well-established, safe and effective treatment for paracetamol toxicity, and thus fomepezil is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Administering N-acetylcysteine (NAC) immediately slows down liver damage in paracetamol toxicity","Most hospitals/health networks will have their own local guidelines developed for paracetamol toxicity. It is very helpful to refer to them first in management of such patients"],"references":["Nickson C. Acute paracetamol toxicity [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2020 [cited 2023May1]. Available from: https://litfl.com/acute-paracetamol-toxicity/","Dargan PI, Jones AL. Acetaminophen poisoning: an update for the intensivist. Crit Care. 2002 Apr;6(2):108-10. Epub 2002 Mar 14. Review. PubMed PMID: 11983032; PubMed Central PMCID: PMC137288."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12497"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-01T13:40:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-01T13:40:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"